result.execSummary:
The defendant Elizabeth A Snider was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Disorderly Conduct. This is not a criminal offense and results only in a money penalty for this offense.

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: Adjustments done this date.  On 7-26-17 KK receipted $25 (receipt 17 R 002960) to see how it would get applied as we noticed that the receipt on 6-30-17 went to the fine and not restitution.  The receipt on 7-26-17 went to RHT like it should have but was voided as it was a test payment.  After voiding the receipt out we noticed that the $25 was still in RHT.  After being on the phone several times with CCAP and after doing several adjustments that did not work I decided to modify the the LOTH acct up to show that a payment was NOT made on 6-30-17 to the LOTH acct.  When you look at the LOTH assessment it shows that a payment of $25 was made but that is not true.  I also modified the REST down as the $25 payment on June 30th should have went there.
